## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException catch with ResetAbort.

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. The fix is cooperative cancellation via `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is not null)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException);
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Old (.NET Framework) | New (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(work, token)` | Task-based model; token enables cancellation |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` | Blocking wait; cancellation handles the timeout |
| `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Cooperative cancellation replaces forced abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No equivalent needed — cancellation is cooperative |

### Key pitfalls for this migration

1. **`Func<T> work` doesn't check the token** — if `work` is a long-running computation that never yields, cancellation won't interrupt it. The token only prevents *scheduling*; it won't stop already-running code. To fix, change the signature:
   ```csharp
   public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
   {
       using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
       var token = cts.Token;
       var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
       // ... same catch logic
   }
   ```
   Then callers must call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints.

2. **Blocking I/O won't be interrupted** — if `work` calls `socket.Receive()` or `Thread.Sleep()`, the token can't break in. Use async overloads (`await stream.ReadAsync(buffer, token)`) or replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`.

3. **Always dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it holds internal timers. The `using` statement handles this.

4. **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** — the `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures we only catch *our* timeout, not an unrelated cancellation.

### Behavioral difference to be aware of

The old code **forcibly killed** the thread on timeout — the work stopped no matter what. The new code **requests** cancellation. If `work` ignores the token, it keeps running on a thread-pool thread even after `TimeoutException` is thrown. This is the fundamental paradigm shift from preemptive to cooperative cancellation in modern .NET.
